descriptionMd:
I love running into brief, evocative messages on the street. These short, pithy, fleeting symbols are sometimes the exact thing that we need to hear at the moment we encounter them and jolt us out of our hurry and routine. Wi-Fi networks are like the digital equivalent—a public space that we visit in order to rush into the flood of digital information that is being connected in the modern world. I wanted to recreate this interruption in our digital space: to give a chance to hear something that we need and invite a moment of pause before entering the flood. 
&nbsp;
I began using my personal phone hotspot to send and share little messages with people in the Wi-Fi networks page. And I just wanted to add a little moment of whimsy or inject some play into this space that's usually so functional and so transient, but still is something that so many people use every day. And so I started doing phrases like, "You are enough," "Good work today," "Thanks for all your hard work," "I'm grateful for you." And these messages that can't be a little silly but seen in this weird place maybe have more impact. And I started playing with catering it to the specific place that I was going to at any given moment. So when I was on the plane, I changed it to have a nice flight. When I was in the bathroom, I changed it to "Good luck" in there. And... When I was in a restaurant, I said like the food here is really good.
